3200 newborn babies in Sabah have no reported raw paper due to special anti-counterfeiting paper out of stockKota Kinabalu, Kota Kinabalu, July 11, 2017-The Sabah National Registration Department (NRD) said that it has been unable to issue birth certificates to newborn babies since early October due to the use of special anti-counterfeiting paper stocks. So far, 3200 people have been affected. However, the director of the department, Kailu Aminus, assured that all the information of babies who have applied for birth certificates has been recorded in the system and will be reissued when the anti-counterfeiting paper arrives next week. He said at a press conference,In response to an online media report that Sabah newspaper had been printing waste paper for 10 months, he explained that the problem had arisen two months ago and Sarawak was facing the same problem. "One of the reasons is that the China manufacturers of special anti-counterfeiting paper are affected by the epidemic, resulting in delays in their delivery to our country." He explained that the anti-counterfeiting paper used in Sabah 's raw paper is different from other regions, so it is not possible to borrow stocks from other states.The final printing will be done immediately after returning to Sabah. It is estimated that the application will be handed over to the applicant in 2 working days (December 20)."" We will inform the applicant to collect the birth certificate at the local branch office." He added that Sabah has issued 24,801 birth papers so far this year.
